John Edward: Language skills essential for global citizens
The independent schools in Scotland have an excellent track record of academic excellence, and this has continued in 2018 with a series of excellent exam results, and further individual and collective success in sport, art, music and other community-wide initiatives.
With over 30,000 pupils in Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), aim to provide the best service to their pupils and parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare their pupils for further and higher education, their chosen careers and their place as global citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a tailored school curriculum, we see that modern languages remain popular and desirable subjects within schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "When you talk to someone in a language they understand, you reach their head.
When you speak to him in his own language, you reach his heart.
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely solely on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From the recent results of this year's exams, we can conclude that languages are at the top of the rankings, with the highest pass rates among independent schools.
In total, 68 percent of students studying foreign languages scored high.
Data collected from 74 SCIS schools shows that 72 percent of students scored high (A) in Mandarin, while 72 percent of students scored high in German, 69 percent of students in French and 63 percent of students in Spanish.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now valued as a subject as much as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent school curricula and elsewhere.
A survey by the UK's Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 found that 17 percent of the barriers to filling vacancies were attributed to a lack of language skills, according to employers.
Language skills are therefore becoming increasingly important in preparing young people for their future careers.
As more and more jobs require language skills, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career a person chooses, if he has learned a second language, he will have a real advantage in the future with such a skill for life.
Direct communication with people from abroad automatically gives a multilingual person a competitive edge.
According to a YouGov poll of more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation.
This is why investing in language education is important for today's children.
Being able to speak multiple languages, especially those of emerging economies, will give children a better chance of finding meaningful jobs.
In Scotland, schools choose the languages they teach.
Some schools will focus on the more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages that are most important to the UK as they look ahead to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interests, there will always be different languages to choose from in independent schools, with teachers who specialize in this field.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing a learning environment that prepares children and gives them the skills they need to succeed, regardless of the future.
It is not currently denied that languages remain vital for the future of the country in a global business environment, so this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should actually be considered as 'international communication skills'.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
It's got to be fair.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
