Harvard students are taking a course on the importance of adequate rest
A new course at Harvard University this year is making sure all students get more sleep, in an effort to combat the growing macho culture where it seems cool to study all night and drink a lot of caffeine.
One professor found that students at the world's largest university often have no idea of the basic principles of self-care.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist affiliated with Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which, as far as he knows, is unique in the United States.
He got the idea to start the course after he gave a talk about the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
"At the end of my talk, a girl came up to me and said, 'Why don't I hear this now, in my senior year?'
She said no one had ever told her how important sleep was, which surprised me, he told The Telegraph.
The course, which is being organised for the first time this year, will explain to students the basic principles of how good sleep habits help improve academic and athletic performance and how they also promote their overall wellbeing.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said the university decided to organize the course when it was found that students were experiencing severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The course lasts one hour and includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one of the sections, students see an image of a bedroom, where they click on coffee cups, curtains, exercise equipment and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light and how sleep deprivation affects sports performance, and the importance of a routine sleeping.
In another section, participants were told how long-term sleep deprivation increases the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
Using a campus map with interactive icons, participants are encouraged to reflect on their daily routine.
We know that this will not change the behaviour of the students immediately.
But we think they have a right to know all this, just as people have a right to know what health consequences their choice of cigarettes has, Czeisler added.
The culture of pride in one night's study still exists, he says, and with modern technology and the increasing pressure on students, sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
Ensuring adequate, high-quality sleep should be the student's secret weapon to combat stress, fatigue and anxiety, he said, and even to avoid weight gain, because lack of sleep causes the brain to give them a constant feeling of hunger.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student of chemical and physical biology from California, helped to design the course for Professor Czeisler, who had been a student of the professor's last year when he was a freshman at Harvard.
He said the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to make the course available to everyone on campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all students to follow a similar curriculum before entering the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler advises students to set an alarm before bedtime, not just an alarm to get up, but also to be aware of the harmful effects of the blue light from electronic screens and LEDs, which can disrupt your circadian rhythm, causing you to have trouble falling asleep.
