The inventor of the World Wide Web is planning a new Internet to attack Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, is starting a startup that wants to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
Inrupt, the latest project of the tech legend, is a company based on Berners-Lee's open source platform Solid.
Solid allows users to choose where their data is stored and which persons have access to which information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that "world domination" is the leading thought behind Inrupt.
"We have to do this now", he said of the startup.
"This is a historic moment".
The app uses Solid's technology to enable people to create their own 'personal online data storage' or POD.
It can store contact lists, activity lists, a calendar, a music library and other personal and professional tools.
It's like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify are all available together through one browser and all at the same time.
What makes POD unique is that it is entirely up to the user who has access to what information.
The company calls this "personal empowerment through data".
The idea behind Inrupt, according to CEO John Bruce, is that the company provides the resources, processes and skills needed to make Solid available to everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform bought by IBM, a few developers contracted to work on the project, and a community of volunteer programmers.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world will be able to create their own decentralized apps using the tools available on Inrupt's website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team will not be having conversations with "Facebook and Google about whether or not to introduce a complete transformation that will completely change all their business models at once".
"We're not asking for their permission".
In a post on Medium published Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that the "mission (of Inrupt) is to deliver the commercial energy and ecosystem that helps protect the integrity and quality of the new web, which is built on Solid".
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been an influential voice in the debate on net neutrality.
Even after launching Inrupt, Berners-Lee will continue to serve as founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
"I'm incredibly optimistic about this new era for the web", Berners-Lee added.
