Tom Daley felt inferior because of his sexual orientation
Olympic sprinter Tom Daley says that he felt inferior in his youth because of his sexual orientation, but that this gave him the motivation to become successful.
The 24-year-old said that until he went to further education, he did not realize that 'not everyone is like me.'
In an interview with Desert Island Discs on Radio 4 with Lauren Laverne, he said he had spoken out about gay rights to give others "hope".
He also said that parenting had contributed to his underestimating of winning at the Olympics.
Kirsty Young, the regular host of the long-running show, has taken a few months off due to illness.
Appearing as a hook on Laverne's first program, Daley told him that he felt "less" than others when he was young because "it was socially unacceptable to like both girls and boys".
He said: "To this day, those feelings, the feeling of being less and the feeling of being different, are really existing facts that have given me the strength to be successful".
He wanted to prove that he was "someone" so that he would not disappoint people if they eventually found out what he was.
The two-time Olympic bronze medalist has become a prominent campaigner for the LGBT community, using his presence at the Commonwealth Games in Australia this year to call on more countries to decriminalize homosexuality.
He said he spoke because he felt happy that he could live openly without further consequences and that he wanted to give others "hope".
The three-time world champion said that falling in love with a man, American filmmaker Dustin Lance Back, whom he met in 2013, "completely surprised me".
Daley married the Oscar winner last year, who is 20 years older than him, but said the age difference was never a problem.
"When you have to endure so much at such a young age", he participated in his first Olympics at the age of 14 and his father died of cancer three years later, it is hard to find someone in your own age group who has experienced the same highs and lows.
The couple became parents of a son named Robert Ray Black-Daley in June and Daley said his "whole perspective" had changed.
"If you had asked me this question last year, I would have said it was all about winning a gold medal", he said.
"But you know what, there are more important things on earth than winning Olympic gold medals.
My Olympic gold medal is Robbie".
His son has the same name as his father who died in 2011 at age 40 after being diagnosed with brain cancer.
Daley said his father hadn't accepted that he was going to die and one of the last things he had asked was if they had already gotten the tickets to London 2012 because he wanted to sit in the front row.
"I couldn't get it over my heart to say, you won't be there to sit in the front row, Dad", he said.
"I held his hand when he stopped breathing and not until his breath actually stopped and he died, I could finally admit that he was not invincible", he said.
The following year, Daley competed in the 2012 Olympics and won bronze.
"I knew I'd dreamed of this all my life. Diving in front of a home crowd at the Olympics is the best feeling I've ever had", he said.
It was also the inspiration for his first musical choice, Proud by Heather Small, which had grabbed him hard on the way to the games and which still gave him a bad skin.
