The new German warship has been postponed again
The newest frigate of the German Navy should have entered service in 2014 to replace the outdated Cold War warships, but it will take at least another year to be ready, due to faulty systems and rising costs, local media reported.
The commissioning of the 'Rheinland-Pfalz', the lead ship in the brand new Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates, has now been postponed until the first half of 2019, according to Die Zeit newspaper quoting a military spokesman.
The vessel was to have joined the Navy in 2014, but the worrying problems after delivery have plagued the fate of the ambitious project.
The four Baden-Wuerttemberg-class vessels ordered by the Navy in 2007 are intended to replace the outdated Bremen-class frigates.
As far as we know, they have a powerful cannon, a range of air defense and anti-ship missiles, and some kind of stealth technology, such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic features.
Other important features are longer maintenance cycles, it should be possible to deploy the latest frigates for up to two years in a row, far from home ports.
The continuing delays mean, however, that the advanced warships, designed to enable Germany to project its power overseas, are already obsolete by the time they are put into service, notes Die Zeit.
The fatal F125 frigate made headlines last year when the German Navy officially refused to commission the vessel and sent it back to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This was the first time the Navy sent a ship back to a shipbuilder after delivery.
Little is known about the reasons behind this return, but German media cited a number of crucial 'software and hardware flaws' that would render the warship useless if deployed on a combat mission.
Software defects were particularly important because the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class ships are operated by a crew of about 120 sailors, half the manpower of the older Bremen-class frigates.
It was also found that the ship was seriously overweight, which would reduce performance and limit the Navy's ability to carry out further upgrades.
The 'Rheinland-Pfalz' weighs 7,000 tons, twice the size of similar class ships used by the Germans in World War II.
In addition to the defective hardware, the price tag for the entire project, including the training of the crew, is also a problem.
It is said that this has reached a staggering €3.1 billion, compared with the original €2.2 billion.
The problems facing the latest frigates are becoming more important because of recent warnings that the German navy is declining in power.
Earlier this year Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German parliamentary defence committee, admitted that the navy actually "lacks deployable ships".
The official said that over time the problem has grown like a snowball, because old ships were taken out of service but no replacement ships were delivered.
He complained that none of the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates were yet available for enlistment in the Navy.
The National Trust is listening to the secret life of bats
A new study on a farm in the Scottish Highlands tries to reveal how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
The hope is that the findings will shed new light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and will contribute to future conservation activities.
The study, conducted by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland, follows the common and small dwarf mouse, the brown giant caterpillar mouse and the water caterpillar at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment is placed at key locations around the estate to monitor the bat's activities throughout the season.
NTS staff and volunteers will also be conducting mobile tests using handheld sensors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of the bat's cries and what kind of action it is.
A map of the habitat and a report are then produced to provide a detailed picture of their behaviour on a landscape scale.
Rob Dewar, NTS's conservation adviser, hopes the results will show which areas of habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by the species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management, such as creating pastures and how best to maintain forests for bats and similar species.
The population of bats in Scotland and the rest of the UK has declined significantly over the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development activities that affect habitat and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lightning can also pose a risk, as can flycatchers and certain chemical treatments of building materials and attacks by domestic cats.
Bats are not actually blind.
However, their nocturnal hunting habits make their ears more useful than their eyes when catching prey.
They use advanced echo-location techniques to determine the position of insects and obstacles in their flight path.
At the NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, bats are taken very seriously.
The NTS has ten trained experts, who regularly carry out inspections, inspections of beds and sometimes rescue operations.
The organisation has even set up the first and only bat reserve in Scotland at the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, where eight out of the ten species of bats in Scotland live.
Landscape administrator David Thompson says the estate is the ideal territory for bats.
"Here in Threave, we have a great bat environment", he said.
"We have the old buildings, many very old trees and the right habitat.
But there is still so much not known about bats, and therefore the work we do here and elsewhere will help us better understand what they need to thrive".
It stresses the importance of monitoring bats before maintenance work is carried out, as the possible unintentional destruction of a nesting site could lead to the death of 400 female bats and their young, potentially wiping out a whole local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill, harass or disturb them or to destroy their habitat.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scotland's official for the Bat Conservation Trust, has asked the public to contribute to help.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and we just don't know how many of our species are doing with their populations".
