Foreign buyers will have to pay higher rates when they buy a house in the UK
Foreign buyers will have to pay higher fees when they buy a house in the UK and the proceeds will be used to help the homeless under new Conservative plans
This action will have to neutralize Corbyn's success in attracting young voters
The increase in wages is charged to non-taxable persons in the UK
The Treasury expects this to raise £120 million a year to help the homeless.
Foreign buyers will have to pay higher fees when they buy a house in the UK and the extra proceeds will be used to help the homeless, Theresa May will announce today.
This action is seen as an attempt to neutralize the success of Jeremy Corbyn, who is attracting young voters with promises to provide more affordable housing and to tell this story to high earners.
The increase in wages is charged to individuals and companies that do not pay taxes in the UK, with the additional proceeds being used in an effort by the government to combat homelessness.
The surcharge, which is above the current levels, including the higher levels introduced two years ago for second homes and homes purchased for rent, may be up to 3%.
The Ministry of Finance expects to raise up to £120 million a year.
It is estimated that 13 percent of new buildings in London are bought by people outside the UK, which pushes up prices and makes it difficult for beginners to get a foot in the door.
Many prosperous areas in the country, especially the capital, have become virtually 'ghost towns' because of the high number of foreign buyers who spend most of their time abroad.
This new policy comes just weeks after Boris Johnson had pleaded for a reduction in the levy to help young people buy their first home.
He accused large construction firms of keeping prices high by buying land and not using it and called on May to cancel quotas on affordable housing to repair the "housing shame" in Britain.
Corbyn has announced a remarkable series of housing reforms, including rent caps and an end to eviction 'without negligence'.
He also wants to give local governments more opportunities to build new homes.
May said: "Last year I said I wanted to devote my time as prime minister to restoring the 'British Dream', that life will be better for every new generation.
