The summer heat wave has boosted the revenues of UK pubs struggling to survive, but has also put more pressure on restaurant chains.
Pub and bar groups saw sales rise 2.7 percent in July, but restaurant revenue fell 4.8 percent, the figures show.
Peter Martin, of the business consultancy CGA, which compiled the figures, said: "Continuing sunshine and England's longer-than-expected participation in the World Cups meant that July showed a similar pattern to June, when pubs had 2.8 percent more sales, with the difference that restaurants were now getting even harder.
The 1.8 percent drop in restaurant sales in June only worsened in July.
Pubs and bars that focused on selling liquor performed far better, with better like-for-like growth than restaurants that were down.
Pubs that also focus on selling food are also members of the sun, but not as dramatically as the restaurants.
It seems that people only go out to drink.
In pubs and bars under management, sales of beverages were 6.6 percent higher for the month, while food sales were 3 percent lower".
Paul Newman of RSM, an analyst for the leisure and hospitality industry, said: "These results continue the trend we've seen since the end of April.
